      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your lower back pain during deadlifts is a common sign that your form is shifting too much weight to the lumbar region rather than driving the lift with your legs. This usually happens when the bar path is too straight, your hip hinge is too shallow, or your core isn't fully braced to stabilize the load. To fix it, focus on keeping a tight core, hinging at the hips first, and letting the bar travel close to your shins. If you feel your back working too hard, try shortening the range of motion at the start of the set and ensure your feet are shoulder-width apart. You might also consider adding a slight knee bend to engage the quads more effectively. Consistently checking your alignment against a mirror or using a video camera will help you spot any lingering issues.",
